'''Conditional short-circuit current''' is defined as the value of the [[alternating current]] (a.c) component of a prospective current, which a switch without integral [[short-circuit]] protection, but protected by a suitable short circuit protective device (SCPD) in series, can withstand for the operating time of the current under specified test conditions. It may be understood to be the RMS value of the maximum permissible current over a specified time interval (t<sub>0</sub>,t<sub>1</sub>) and operating conditions. The [[International Electrotechnical Commission|IEC]]<ref>IEC 62314-1, The International Standard on Solid-State Relays, Ed 1, Section 3.1.11</ref> definition is critiqued to be open to interpretation.<ref>{{cite book|last1=[[Vladimir Igorevich Gurevich|Gurevich]]|first1=Vladimir|title=Digital protective relays: problems and solutions|date=2011|publisher=CRC Press|location=Boca Raton|isbn=978-1-4398-3785-6|page=360}}</ref>
<math>I = \sqrt {\frac{1}{t_1-t_0} \int_{t_0}^{t_1} i^2(t) dt }</math>
